text: Marcus Tullius Cicero-- From Wikipedia:  Though he was an accomplished orator and successful lawyer, Cicero believed his political career was his most important achievement. It was during his consulship that the Second Catilinarian Conspiracy attempted to overthrow the government through an attack on the city by outside forces, *and Cicero suppressed the revolt by executing five conspirators without due process.* During the chaotic latter half of the 1st century BC marked by civil wars and the dictatorship of Gaius Julius Caesar, Cicero championed a return to the traditional republican government.  Following Julius Caesar's death Cicero became an enemy of Mark Antony in the ensuing power struggle, attacking him in a series of speeches. He was proscribed as an enemy of the state by the Second Triumvirate and consequently executed by soldiers operating on their behalf in 43 BC after having been intercepted during attempted flight from the Italian peninsula. His severed hands and head were then, as a final revenge of Mark Antony, displayed in the Roman Forum.

text: I lived in albuquerque for 26 years...i took my kids to Juarez in 2005 - we walked across the border and spent a few hours there. That was before it got really dangerous there. This is a great movie. Its gritty - there were always conversations in abq about this subject...great to see the sandias and shots of abq in the film...I remember when my friend shani was looking for locations...she stayed in T or C for a few months scouting the place out. She'd come back to abq and tell me stories - so i went to see it last night - Ive been homesick for new mexico - fall is always lovely there...what I didnt expect in the last scene (well last shot really) was to see my friend Kim as silvios wife - staring off into the distance...I wanted to blurt out "there's Kim" I just married her and her new husband ryan 5 months ago on venice beach. I've known Kim since she was in high school... we've known each other for about 30 years now - that was a nice surprise....I just remember when she was in killer cops! It made me crave a green chile breakfast burrito - you cant get them anywhere except the new mexico with hatch green chile. frontier and garcias has the best! #hungry #sicario #drugcartel #newmexico #thebridge #frontier #breakfast New Mexico is always best in the fall - the smells - the changing colors....ps i wish FX hadnt cancelled The Bridge that was a gripping TV series about this subject too

Nobody wins the war on drugs, because a war on drugs is a war on the principle of the individual right to own private property. text: Quite a few people seem to be missing major themes and points this film makes. It is very much a dark toned thriller and drama, not action or adventure. It is ultimately questioning the far spectrum of U.S. drug enforcement and the lengths they will go to fight the cartels. Cautioning how they may become the monsters they fight by playing on their level. Black operations, threats, kidnappings, torture, murder, and spree killings are all shown in the film, perpetrated by the CIA and Cartels alike. In the end it asks if we really want conflicts to escalate into insanity or take a step back. Even if dramatized, It is a film with a powerful message.

text: I regret not seeing Sicario in theaters. I really do. This movie is a motherfucking masterpiece! It's well written and perfectly acted; and not nominating this movie for Best Actor in a Supporting Role (Benicio Del Toro) and Best Picture should've been a crime. Del Toro gave the performance of a lifetime that rivals with Javier Bardem's portrayal of Anton Chigurh from No Country For Old Men. Denis Villeneuve is one of our greatest directors working today, and I am very much looking forward to his Blade Runner sequel. If you want to go watch a well crafted and intelligent crime thriller, then Sicario is just for you!
